Lettuce: Lattice Cryptography Library

Summary for transcript readers:

Lettuce is a Rust-based cryptography library (94.7% Rust, 4.6% TeX, 0.7% JavaScript) implementing lattice-based cryptographic primitives over finite fields and quotient rings.

Core Components

Constructions:

  • hidden_rics - Linear complexity NIZK argument of RICS (Rank-1 Constraint Systems)

Commitment Schemes:

  • BDLOP
  • Transparent inner product
  • Lattice Hash

Probability Distributions:

  • Gaussian
  • Ternary

Algebraic Structures:

  • Field scalars
  • Ring elements
  • Matrices
  • Vectors
  • RICS (Rank-1 Constraint Systems)

Purpose

Provides healthy lattice utilities for post-quantum cryptographic constructions, zero-knowledge proofs, and commitment schemes based on lattice assumptions.

Documentation

  • docs.rs/lettuce
  • crates.io/lettuce

This is an append-only transcript that will be rendered as HTML and committed to version control.

Lettuce Cryptography Concepts

Constructions

hidden_rics (Linear complexity NIZK arg of RICS)

  • NIZK: Non-Interactive Zero-Knowledge proof system
  • RICS: Rank-1 Constraint System - algebraic representation for computation verification
  • Linear complexity: Efficient scaling with input size
  • Enables proving knowledge of a solution without revealing it

Commitment Schemes

BDLOP

  • Lattice-based commitment scheme
  • Named after authors (likely Baum-Damgrd-Lyubashevsky-Ostrovsky-Peikert or similar)
  • Cryptographic primitive for binding to a value without revealing it

Transparent inner product

  • Commitment scheme based on inner product arguments
  • "Transparent" implies no trusted setup required
  • Used for vector commitments and proof systems

Lattice Hash

  • Hash function constructed from lattice problems
  • Post-quantum secure hashing
  • Leverages hardness of lattice mathematical problems

Probability Distributions

Gaussian

  • Normal distribution over lattice structures
  • Used for noise sampling in lattice cryptography
  • Critical for security proofs in lattice schemes

Ternary

  • Distribution over {-1, 0, 1} or similar small set
  • Efficient representation and computation
  • Common in lattice signature schemes

Structures

Field scalar

  • Element of a finite field
  • Basic arithmetic unit for computations

Ring element

  • Element of a quotient ring (polynomial ring mod ideal)
  • Foundation for Ring-LWE and similar constructions

Matrix

  • 2D array of field/ring elements
  • Used in linear algebra operations for lattice constructions

Vector

  • 1D array of field/ring elements
  • Represents lattice points or polynomial coefficients

RICS (Rank-1 Constraint System)

  • System of equations: (Ax) (Bx) = Cx
  • Arithmetic circuit representation
  • Used for general-purpose zero-knowledge proofs

Discrete Concepts in Lattice Cryptography

Discrete Gaussian Distributions

A discrete Gaussian is a probability distribution over integers () or lattice points that approximates a continuous Gaussian bell curve.

Key properties:

  • Centered at some point (mean)
  • Spread determined by parameter (standard deviation)
  • Probability of sampling integer x: proportional to exp(-||x-||/)
  • Only assigns probability to discrete points, not continuous values

Why important:

  • Adds "noise" to lattice cryptography schemes
  • The noise makes problems computationally hard (Learning With Errors)
  • Must be discrete because cryptographic operations happen over integers/lattices
  • The Gaussian shape provides provable security guarantees

Practical use: Sample random integers where most values cluster near the center, with exponentially decreasing probability for outliers.

Statistical Security

Statistical security means an adversary with unlimited computational power still cannot break the scheme except with negligible probability.

Contrast with computational security:

  • Computational: adversary limited by polynomial time computation
  • Statistical: adversary has infinite time/power, still fails

How it works:

  • Two distributions are statistically close if their total variation distance is negligible
  • Even examining all possible values, an attacker cannot distinguish real from simulated data
  • Security comes from information theory, not hardness assumptions

In lattice crypto:

  • Often achieved by adding enough Gaussian noise that traces are "smoothed out"
  • Parameters chosen so statistical distance < 2 for security parameter k
  • Stronger than computational security but may require larger parameters

Example: If a protocol leaks some value v + noise where noise is drawn from a wide enough Gaussian, even an all-powerful adversary cannot recover v because the noise distribution hides it information-theoretically.

Polynomial Rings

A polynomial ring is the set of all polynomials with coefficients from some base ring (like integers or finite field ), with arithmetic performed modulo some polynomial.

Structure:

  • Base: [x] means polynomials with integer coefficients
  • Example element: 3x + 7x - 2x + 5
  • Operations: add/subtract/multiply polynomials normally

Quotient by a polynomial:

  • Work in [x]/(x + 1) means "mod out by x + 1"
  • When x appears, replace it with -1
  • All polynomials have degree < n
  • Creates a finite-dimensional structure

Example with n=4:

  • Ring: [x]/(x + 1)
  • Elements look like: a + ax + ax + ax
  • Multiplication: (x)(x) = x = xx = x(-1) = -x

Why useful in crypto:

  • Compact representation: one polynomial = n coefficients
  • Fast multiplication using FFT/NTT
  • Security from Ring-LWE hardness assumption
  • Efficient homomorphic operations

Practical intuition: Think of it as vector arithmetic with a special multiplication rule defined by the modulus polynomial.

R1CS as Number-Theoretic Program Representation

R1CS (Rank-1 Constraint System) represents program execution as a system of quadratic equations over a finite field.

Basic form: Each constraint looks like: (Ax) (Bx) = Cx

  • A, B, C are matrices
  • x is a vector (witness + public inputs)
  • means element-wise multiplication (Hadamard product)

How it represents programs:

  1. Variables become field elements:
    • Program variables entries in witness vector x
    • All arithmetic happens mod prime p
  2. Operations become constraints:
    • Addition: x = x + x becomes constraint (1x + 1x) (1) = x
    • Multiplication: x = x x becomes constraint (x) (x) = x
    • Constant: x = 5 becomes constraint (x) (1) = 5
  3. Control flow flattens:
    • if/else selector variables and constraints
    • loops unrolled into repeated constraints

Example program:

def program(a, b):
    c = a * b
    d = c + a
    return d == 10

Becomes R1CS:

  • Variables: x = [1, a, b, c, d] (1 is constant)
  • Constraint 1: (b) (a) = c // multiplication
  • Constraint 2: (c + a) (1) = d // addition
  • Constraint 3: (d) (1) = 10 // equality check

Why number-theoretic:

  • All values are field elements (mod prime)
  • Operations follow field arithmetic rules
  • Program correctness = satisfying all equations in the field
  • Enables zero-knowledge: prove you know x satisfying equations without revealing x

Key insight: Any computation can be "compiled" into R1CS, transforming code into pure mathematics where proofs become algebraic statements.

Universal Hash Functions

A universal hash family is a collection of hash functions where collisions are provably rare when the hash function is chosen randomly from the family.

Definition: A family = {h, h, ...} is universal if for any two distinct inputs x y: Pr[h(x) = h(y)] 1/m

where h is chosen randomly from and m is the output range size.

Key property: Even if an adversary knows all functions in the family and can pick the worst-case inputs x and y, a randomly selected hash function will collide on them with only probability 1/m (the "birthday bound").

Example construction: For prime p and outputs mod m:

  • Family: h_{a,b}(x) = ((ax + b) mod p) mod m
  • Parameters a, b chosen randomly from [0, p-1]
  • Simple linear function, but provably universal

Why "universal":

  • Works for any input distribution
  • Security comes from random choice of function, not from hiding the function
  • Adversary can know the entire family structure

In cryptography:

  • Used in commitment schemes
  • Provides collision resistance without complex assumptions
  • Can build MACs: MAC(k,m) = h_k(m) where k selects the hash function
  • Often more efficient than cryptographic hashes for specific applications

Contrast with cryptographic hashes:

  • Cryptographic: one function, computationally hard to find collisions
  • Universal: many functions, information-theoretically rare collisions when randomly chosen

Practical use in lattice crypto: Universal hashing from matrices: h_A(x) = Ax mod q, where A is a random matrix. Collisions are rare due to lattice problem hardness.
